Social determinants of health are nonmedical factors that can affect a person's 
overall health and health outcomes. Where a person is born and the social 
conditions they are born into can affect their risk factors for premature death 
and their life expectancy. In this position paper, the American College of 
Physicians acknowledges the role of social determinants in health, examines the 
complexities associated with them, and offers recommendations on better 
integration of social determinants into the health care system while 
highlighting the need to address systemic issues hindering health equity.

